 essays, a range of academics, economists and political commentators delineate the reactionary course that Ireland has followed since the ignominious demise of the Celtic Tiger. They argue that the forces of neoliberalism have employed the economic crisis they caused to advance policies that are in their own narrow interests, and that the host of regressive measures imposed since the onset of global recession has fundamentally restructured Irish society.The book provides a critical account of a society that has more often than most mapped out the pernicious cycle of boom and bust that remains an essential hallmark of contemporary capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDebts, PublicxIreland. 0aDebts, PubliczIreland. 0aFinancial crisesxHistoryx21st centuryxIreland. 0aFinancial criseszIrelandxHistoryy21st century. 0aNeoliberalismxHistoryx21st centuryxIreland. 0aNeoliberalismzIrelandxHistoryy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  aCeltic Tiger.  aCommunity Development Project.  aDepartment of Community.  aIrish Republic.  aIrish economic crash.  aRural and Gaeltacht Affairs.  aUS investment.  aausterity measures.  acapitalist globalisation.  aglobal recession.  aneoliberalism.  apeacetime.  aviolence.  aworld economy.1 aAllen, Kieran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArqueros-Fernández, Francisco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBissett, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoulter, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoulter, Colin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCronin, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinn, Daniel, e